- **`RunSessionHandler`**: Async callback for session lifecycle hooks (runs before/after session)
- **`EnableLegacySse`**: Boolean to enable legacy SSE endpoints at `/sse` and `/message` (2024-11-05 spec)
- **`IdleTimeout`**: TimeSpan for idle session timeout
- **`TimeProvider`**: Custom time provider for testing

---

### 2. **MCP Tools**

#### Attribute Names & Namespaces:

```csharp
// Namespace: ModelContextProtocol.Server

// For class-level discovery
[McpServerToolType]
public class MyToolClass
{
    // Mark individual methods as tools
    [McpServerTool(Name = "my_tool", Description = "...")]
    public string MyTool(string param1, int param2)
    {
        return "result";
    }
}
```

#### Registration Methods:

```csharp
// Namespace: Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection

// Option 1: Register generic type (scans for [McpServerTool] attributes)
builder
    .WithTools<MyToolClass>(jsonSerializerOptions)
    .WithTools<MyToolClass>(instance, jsonSerializerOptions);

// Option 2: Register from assembly
builder.WithToolsFromAssembly(
    assembly: Assembly.GetExecutingAssembly(),
    serializerOptions: jsonSerializerOptions);

// Option 3: Register pre-built tool instances
builder.WithTools(new[] { tool1, tool2 });

// Option 4: Register tool types
builder.WithTools(new[] { typeof(MyToolClass) }, jsonSerializerOptions);
```

#### Method Signatures:

```csharp
// Generic registration
IMcpServerBuilder WithTools<TToolType>(
    this IMcpServerBuilder builder,
    JsonSerializerOptions? serializerOptions = null);

IMcpServerBuilder WithTools<TToolType>(
    this IMcpServerBuilder builder,
    TToolType target,
    JsonSerializerOptions? serializerOptions = null);

// Assembly-based discovery
IMcpServerBuilder WithToolsFromAssembly(
    this IMcpServerBuilder builder,
    Assembly? toolAssembly = null,
    JsonSerializerOptions? serializerOptions = null);

// Direct tool registration
IMcpServerBuilder WithTools(
    this IMcpServerBuilder builder,
    IEnumerable<ModelContextProtocol.Server.McpServerTool> tools);

IMcpServerBuilder WithTools(
    this IMcpServerBuilder builder,
    IEnumerable<Type> toolTypes,
    JsonSerializerOptions? serializerOptions = null);
```

#### Attribute Details:

**`[McpServerToolType]`** - Class-level attribute
```csharp
// Namespace: ModelContextProtocol.Server
[AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Class)]
public class McpServerToolTypeAttribute
```
- Marks a class for automatic tool discovery via `WithToolsFromAssembly`
- Required methods must have `[McpServerTool]` attribute

**`[McpServerTool]`** - Method-level attribute
```csharp
// Namespace: ModelContextProtocol.Server
[AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Method)]
public class McpServerToolAttribute
```
- Marks individual methods as MCP tools
- Parameters sourced from `CallToolRequestParams.Arguments` dictionary
- Automatically handles parameter marshaling and return value serialization

---

### 3. **MCP Resources**

#### Attribute Names & Namespaces:

```csharp
// Namespace: ModelContextProtocol.Server

// For class-level discovery
[McpServerResourceType]
public class MyResourceClass
{
    // Mark individual methods/properties as resources
    [McpServerResource(Uri = "resource://example", Name = "example")]
    public string GetResource()
    {
        return "content";
    }

    // Templated resource
    [McpServerResource(Uri = "resource://files/{id}", Name = "file")]
    public string GetFile(string id)
    {
        return $"Content of file {id}";
    }
}
```

#### Registration Methods:

```csharp
// Namespace: Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection

// Option 1: Register generic type (scans for [McpServerResource] attributes)
builder
    .WithResources<MyResourceClass>()
    .WithResources<MyResourceClass>(instance);

// Option 2: Register from assembly
builder.WithResourcesFromAssembly(
    resourceAssembly: Assembly.GetExecutingAssembly());

// Option 3: Register pre-built resource instances
builder.WithResources(new[] { resource1, resource2 });

// Option 4: Register resource types
builder.WithResources(new[] { typeof(MyResourceClass) });
```

#### Method Signatures:

```csharp
// Generic registration
IMcpServerBuilder WithResources<TResourceType>(
    this IMcpServerBuilder builder);

IMcpServerBuilder WithResources<TResourceType>(
    this IMcpServerBuilder builder,
    TResourceType target);

// Assembly-based discovery
IMcpServerBuilder WithResourcesFromAssembly(
    this IMcpServerBuilder builder,
    Assembly? resourceAssembly = null);

// Direct resource registration
IMcpServerBuilder WithResources(
    this IMcpServerBuilder builder,
    IEnumerable<ModelContextProtocol.Server.McpServerResource> resources);

IMcpServerBuilder WithResources(
    this IMcpServerBuilder builder,
    IEnumerable<Type> resourceTypes);
```

#### Attribute Details:

**`[McpServerResourceType]`** - Class-level attribute
```csharp
// Namespace: ModelContextProtocol.Server
[AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Class)]
public class McpServerResourceTypeAttribute
```
- Marks a class for automatic resource discovery via `WithResourcesFromAssembly`
- Required members must have `[McpServerResource]` attribute

**`[McpServerResource]`** - Method/Property-level attribute
```csharp
// Namespace: ModelContextProtocol.Server
[AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Method | AttributeTargets.Property)]
public class McpServerResourceAttribute
```
- Applied to methods or properties that should be exposed as resources
- Supports both direct URIs (e.g., `resource://example`) and templated URIs (e.g., `resource://files/{id}`)
- Special parameters automatically bound:
  - `CancellationToken` - bound from server cancellation
  - `IServiceProvider` - bound from `RequestContext<ReadResourceRequestParams>`
  - `McpServer` - bound to the MCP server instance
- URI template parameters are automatically extracted and bound to method parameters

---

### 4. **Resources vs. Resource Templates**

The key distinction is in the `McpServerResource` class properties:

#### **`ProtocolResourceTemplate`** (Always available)
```csharp
// Namespace: ModelContextProtocol.Protocol
public ResourceTemplate ProtocolResourceTemplate { get; }
```
- **Definition**: The template definition as per MCP protocol specification
- **When used**: Always returns a valid instance
- **Purpose**: For resource templates with parameters (e.g., `resource://files/{id}`)
- **Properties**: `Uri` (with template syntax), `Name`, `Description`, `MimeType`, `UriTemplate`, `Annotations`, `Icons`, `Meta`, `IsTemplated`
- **Use case**: When you want to advertise pattern-based resources to clients

#### **`ProtocolResource`** (May be null)
```csharp
// Namespace: ModelContextProtocol.Protocol
public Resource? ProtocolResource { get; }
```
- **Definition**: A concrete resource instance (non-template)
- **When used**: Only when the URI contains NO parameters
- **Returns null when**: The template contains path parameters (e.g., `{id}`)
- **Purpose**: For fixed resources without parameters (e.g., `resource://example`)
- **Properties**: Same as `ResourceTemplate` but represents a concrete resource
- **Use case**: When you want to advertise fixed-URI resources

#### **`IsTemplated`** Property
```csharp
public bool IsTemplated { get; }
```
- Returns `true` if the resource URI contains template parameters
- Returns `false` for direct/concrete resource URIs

#### **Example Distinction**:

```csharp
// Direct Resource (ProtocolResource is not null)
[McpServerResource(Uri = "resource://config")]
public string GetConfig() => "...";
// ProtocolResource âś“ (concrete)
// ProtocolResourceTemplate âś“ (same URI, IsTemplated=false)
// IsTemplated = false

// Templated Resource (ProtocolResource is null)
[McpServerResource(Uri = "resource://files/{fileId}")]
public string GetFile(string fileId) => "...";
// ProtocolResource = null (no concrete URI without parameters)
// ProtocolResourceTemplate âś“ (with template syntax)
// IsTemplated = true
```

#### **Protocol Matching**:
- Clients use `ListResourceTemplatesAsync()` to discover available resource templates
- Clients use `ReadAsync()` with concrete URIs that match `IsMatch(uri)` validation
- The server automatically handles template matching and parameter extraction

---

### 5. **Key Namespaces Summary**

```csharp
// Core server configuration
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

// ASP.NET Core HTTP/SSE transport
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Builder;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Routing;
using ModelContextProtocol.AspNetCore;

// Protocol models (resources, tools, etc.)
using ModelContextProtocol.Protocol;
```

---

### 6. **Complete Minimal Example**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Builder;
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Define tools
[McpServerToolType]
public class Calculator
{
    [McpServerTool(Description = "Add two numbers")]
    public int Add(int a, int b) => a + b;
}

// Define resources
[McpServerResourceType]
public class FileStore
{
    [McpServerResource(Uri = "resource://config")]
    public string GetConfig() => "Configuration data";

    [McpServerResource(Uri = "resource://files/{filename}")]
    public string GetFile(string filename) => $"Content of {filename}";
}

// Register MCP server
builder.Services
    .AddMcpServer()
    .WithTools<Calculator>()
    .WithResources<FileStore>()
    .WithHttpTransport(opts =>
    {
        opts.ConfigureSessionOptions = async (context, options) =>
        {
            // Per-session configuration
        };
    })
    .AddAuthorizationFilters();

var app = builder.Build();
app.MapMcp("/mcp");
app.Run();
```

---

This covers all the essential APIs needed to build a fully functional MCP HTTP server in ASP.NET Core with tools and resources.

